## 2. The Problem — With Evidence

**Financial illiteracy is one of the largest quantifiable unsolved problems facing young adults.**

### Who This Affects

The **16–25 age cohort** represents approximately **45 million people in the United States** (U.S. Census Bureau, 2023). This is the highest-leverage demographic for financial education: habits formed before age 25 predict lifetime wealth accumulation more strongly than any other age-based intervention (CFPB Financial Well-Being Research, 2023). Every year this group goes without structured financial education is a year of compounding returns lost — permanently.

### The Scale

- Only **23 U.S. states** require a personal finance course for high school graduation (NGPF, 2024). Of those, fewer than half require a full semester — the majority require a single unit embedded inside another course.
- **78% of Americans live paycheck to paycheck** (CNBC/SurveyMonkey, 2023) — a statistic that spans all age groups and income levels, including households earning over $100,000 per year. For the 16–25 cohort specifically, the situation is even more acute: a 2023 Bank of America Institute study found that **73% of Gen Z adults** report that financial stress impacts their daily lives, and **67% of adults under 30** have less than one month of expenses saved (Federal Reserve Survey of Consumer Finances, 2022). These numbers demonstrate the problem is behavioral and educational from the very first paycheck — not a condition that develops later in life.
- A 22-year-old who starts investing $200/month earns approximately **$612,000 by age 62** (at 8% historical average market return). A 32-year-old making the identical investment earns only **$272,000** — a $340,000 gap caused entirely by *not knowing to start sooner*.
- The average American who carries a credit card balance pays **$1,380/year in interest** (Federal Reserve, 2024). A basic understanding of how APR compounds would eliminate this cost for most cardholders.
- Student loan borrowers who don't understand income-driven repayment options owe an average of **$37,584** more over their repayment lifetime than borrowers who do (NCES, 2023).

### Why Existing Tools Fail

| Tool | What It Does | What It Fails To Do |
|------|-------------|---------------------|
| **Mint / YNAB** | Tracks spending | Never explains *why* patterns matter or what to do about them |
| **Robinhood** | Lets you trade | Assumes fluency in financial jargon; gamifies risk; no education layer |
| **Investopedia Simulator** | Paper trading | Disconnected from real budgeting; no AI personalization |
| **Credit Karma** | Shows credit score | Static score display; no actionable coaching or simulation |
| **ChatGPT / Claude** | Answers questions | No integrated tools; no access to the user's actual financial data |
| **Khan Academy** | Teaches finance basics | No connection to the user's real numbers; passive learning only |

**The gap:** No tool today combines *learning + budgeting + simulated investing + contextual AI* with knowledge of the user's personal financial situation. Finance Buddy closes that gap.

### Concrete User Scenario

> Marcus is 19, just got his first job, and earns $2,200/month. He opens Google and types "how to save money." He gets 847,000 results. He reads three articles that contradict each other. He closes the tab. He never starts.

> With Finance Buddy: Marcus names his buddy "Finn," completes a 5-minute quiz, and immediately sees: *"Based on your $2,200 income and current spending, Finn recommends setting aside $330/month (15%) — here's exactly how to do it with your current subscriptions."* He acts on it that day.

This is the difference between passive information and contextual guidance.

